  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Chile Flooding &amp; Volcano Eruption  Response</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Community members affected by disasters</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Habitat has distributed 1,200 shelter repair kits in the Atacama region, where 2,000 houses were destroyed, 5,000 suffered major damage and 7,000 have minor damages. 300 shelter repair kits are also being distribuited in the southern area affected by the volcano eruption.  Habitat is working in partnership with the Chilean Red Cross, who is already working in these communities providing psychological support, WASH activities and livelihood recovery programs.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On March 24 2015, an unprecedented amount of rain caused 17 simultaneous flash floods in three regions of northern Chile: Atacama, Antofagasta and Coquimbo. Additionally, three other simultaneous massive emergencies in the south of Chile are testing response capacity: a dry spell that is affecting a large part of southern Chile which is directly linked to 22 wildfires across four regions and the eruption of the Villa Rica Volcano.</narrative>
  </description>
